# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1902 Pittsburgh Pirates** won a second straight National League pennant, by an overwhelming 27.5 game margin over the Brooklyn Superbas.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season] It was the Pirates' first ever 100-win team, and it set franchise records that still stand for winning percentage (.741) and winning percentage at home (.789).
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The team finished with a league-best record of 103–36.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Ginger Beaumont won the batting title with a .357 mark, and Tommy Leach led the league in home runs with six (a major league record for fewest HRs to lead the league).
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Honus Wagner led the league in RBI with 91, and Jack Chesbro led the league with 28 wins.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates led the league in most offensive categories, including runs scored, hits, doubles, triples, RBI, batting average, on-base percentage, and slugging percentage, and were one off the league lead in home runs.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The team's 774 runs exceeded the next-highest total by 142.
[src:1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1902-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The team allowed four home runs during its 1902 season, the fewest in MLB history.
